    ImageUri = "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1577278689329-1914b6814d58?w=600&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8NHx8V2hhdCUyMEklMjBMZWFybmVkJTIwRnJvbSUyMFdvcmtpbmclMjBhdCUyMEFwcGxlfGVufDB8fDB8fHww",
    Description = """
So fun fact, I interned at Apple as a software engineer. Overall, it was an amazing experience. I learned a lot while I was there. And met some amazing people. I wouldn’t trade that experience for any other!
But there was one lesson that’s stuck with me all of these years. It’s something very simple. It’s something you’ve heard about a million times.
ONE THING I feel like Apple really really got right was focus. They had a devotion to focus. It was something that permeated throughout their company culture.
While I don’t believe I’m allowed to say much. Apple is a company that cares a lot about their secrecy. But I think I can say that even before I showed up, I was told that people come to Apple to do their best work, and that focus was key.
Watching that play out was amazing. And it’s something I think about every once in a while.
When you really focus on a few key things, you get the important things done. Super simple. It shouldn’t be surprising. But a lot of us don’t really think about it. But for one reason or another we all end up doing it without thinking about it.
We develop our careers over decades. We gain lifelong hobbies. There are only a few things we are really good at. And all of those things, we had to spend a lot of time and focus to get good at.
One thing that took me a few years to realize, is that patience is key for making focus become truly powerful. You need to focus on the key things for a long period of time. That key element of time, is what allows your skills and results to compound. Only then will your hard work bear great fruit.
Switching your focus rapidly is similar to not having focus at all. So be patient. Focus. Allow your results to compound. And bear fruit. Just like Apple. 😉
""",
