{
    AuthorId = usersArray[2].Id,
    Title = "How Living Together Saved Us Money (and Sanity)",
    ImageUri = "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1653656091328-a1386f72daee?w=600&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MTJ8fEhvdyUyMExpdmluZyUyMFRvZ2V0aGVyJTIwU2F2ZWQlMjBVcyUyME1vbmV5fGVufDB8fDB8fHww",
    Description = """
Society tells us moving away is a necessarily milestone of adulthood. Are we wrong?
A joyful scene including a mother, grandparents and children enjoying each other’s company.
Is there a lesson we can learn from supportive, happy multigenerational households? (Photo: Pexels)
Sometimes you can tell how uncomfortable a subject makes us by how long it takes to be broached in a conversation.
I’m not even talking about politics or religion.
My new acquaintance and I had already chatted about our respective views on a broad array of topics, navigating them with sensitivity and cultivating a pretty great rapport.
It was over an hour into our phone conversation, when my acquaintance asked me, “No judgement about this, but why did you decide to continue living with your parents?”
Ah, I thought, smiling inwardly with familiarity. That question.
He already knew I work full time in a career I love, and have recently finished writing a couple of science fiction thrillers, the first of which is set for release next year. For a recent article I wrote about my writing journey, I was interviewed here: How this novelist uses Medium to promote her novel | by Zulie @ Medium | The Medium Handbook | Oct 2025 |
Given my self-starter personality and obvious optimism about life, my friend’s curiosity was piqued as to why I hadn’t checked off that other conventional rite of passage, which so many take for granted as being a milestone indicator of adulthood: moving away from the nest and living independently.
A woman dancing in celebration in the doorway of a newly purchased home.
Buying one’s first home — a milestone I’ve delayed by choice.
“That’s an interesting question,” I replied, feeling strangely liberated by the opportunity to break open a topic that’s typically awkward to discuss without stirring up a cocktail of defensiveness, discomfort and disagreement.
We’ve all seen the headlines:
· Debt, Delayed Marriages Keeping Millennials From Home Ownership, Fed Report Says (December, 2023)
· Why Gen Z Will Never Leave Home — a Canadian perspective
· The Pew Research Center’s Young adults in the U.S. are reaching key life milestones later than in the past (May, 2023)
National and global economic challenges have also influenced these trends. In Italy, it’s estimated that over 46% of young adults aged 25–34 live with their parents, while in Greece it’s closer to 52%. (Source)
And as the Thanksgiving holiday approaches in the US, our relationship to our families, whether stressful or easy, is increasingly on people’s minds.
Reason #1 — The Financial Upside
“For me, it’s a couple of things,” I began, sharing rent figures for a typical apartment in my city, which can easily range from $1500 — $2,000+ per month, not including utilities and renters’ insurance.
Let’s face it, though — the popular argument for moving away from home as early as possible was never really predicated on the (at times dubious) financial merits of doing so.
It was always more about our ideas of independence and autonomy, and what makes someone an ‘adult.’
For many young adults who moved away from home for college, rejoining parents at the family home may be a strangely unpleasant and even unworkable idea — an emergency option to be considered only if life and career fall apart.
And many parents, including retired empty nesters, make it clear that living alongside their grown children wouldn’t be tolerated beyond a few months.
Conversations sometimes get too heated. Arguments too frequent. Lifestyles, religious adherence, TV-viewing and music choices, and tidiness habits have become too divergent to easily support comfortable cohabitation. Some older generations fear lazy youngsters will rely on them for everything and never develop competence.
Young adults who tolerated tumultuous family dynamics or even abusive conditions while growing up have a further reason for wanting distance between them and their relatives.
Of course, under those conditions, independent living makes sense.
And to be clear, I wouldn’t wish anyone to alter what works for them. This is simply my story — and if you feel similarly, or are curious about an alternate point of view, I welcome you to keep reading.
If not, that’s fine too. If this doesn’t resonate, or even feels triggering, feel free to click away — no hard feelings.
My point is, society has made many young people feel guilty, as though choosing a shared living arrangement is a sure sign we’ve failed as adults, warranting shame.
Meanwhile, in many other societies and cultures, it’s the norm, and often seen as shrewd and financially smart.
Stacks of coins, symbolizing increasing prosperity.
For me, building my financial reserves is a priority. (Pixabay)
As a finance nerd and a pragmatist (with a soft spot for spreadsheets), the idea of paying rent for something I don’t really need, but feel pressured to engage in to prove my adulthood to self and others, feels like a questionable move, and doesn’t appeal to me.
For me, saving and investing that money is simply a far more lucrative option, and fits better with my long-term financial goals — not dissimilar to Sarah Ahn, the Korean-American who shared her views on TikTok and wrote this piece for Yahoo Insider: I’m a 28-year-old living with my parents by choice. I wish that moving out in your 20s wasn’t the American norm.
I consider myself pretty fortunate. Not only do I enjoy good relations with my parents (my mum, an educator and my dad, a retired therapist), now in their golden years, but the strong work ethic they fostered in my sister and me as teenagers, helped create an atmosphere in which sharing expenses and household responsibilities allows mutual benefits.
Not least of which is less spending on dining out or ordering home-delivered meals, since in my experience, sharing kitchen duties means there’s always at least one spatula-twirling home chef available, eager to dust off a favorite recipe. (The health benefits and shared creativity aren’t bad either).
A young woman prepares meals at home.
Cooking at home, an opportunity for creative expression — and saving money (Unsplash)
I’m happy to contribute to my household in multiple ways, and do so with pride and purpose. Sure, we have our differences of opinion sometimes. We’re human. But I would humbly suggest that, where possible, learning to work it out with one’s parents may be as profoundly valuable a life skill-set as learning to share a dorm with strangers in college ever was.
Yet, in modern society, after the age of eighteen, the stigma associated with sharing a home with one’s family/relatives is still enormous, and in too many cases, unnecessarily burdensome.
My question is, at what point does pragmatism, and the joy of my pursuing my personal choice, outweigh discomfort at what other people might think?
Reason #2 — Better mental health
But as I shared with my curious friend in our conversation, there are multiple reasons for my choice.
According to Psychology Today’s How Living Alone Increases the Risk of Depression (Nov 30, 2024):
“These days there are a greater number of single-person households than there used to be.
Whether due to never having married, separation, divorce, or widowhood, nearly 1 in 3 people in Western countries live by themselves.
Like feelings of loneliness, physical social isolation may be a risk factor for many conditions related to physical health (e.g., cardiovascular disease, stroke, diabetes, premature mortality) and mental health, particularly depression.”
A woman sits alone and isolated on a park bench — an image symbolizing the growing loneliness epidemic.
In 2024, U.S. Surgeon General Dr. Vivek Murthy declared loneliness to be an epidemic. (Photo: Unsplash)
During past setbacks, my emotional resilience was greatly bolstered by gritty wisdom and face-to-face conversations my parents were able to share with me. Those tough, tearful talks, and no-strings love coupled with space to relaunch my career saved me considerable therapy bills, and proved invaluable.
Indeed, rebuilding my confidence whilst relaunching my career would have been far tougher and potentially prolonged, had I simultaneously been one of the millions grappling with loneliness and increased isolation.
According to a 2018 study published in the peer-reviewed journal SSM Population Health, Living with parents or grandparents increases social capital and survival, “multi-generational household living arrangements have increased in the U.S.” and may increase life expectancy. And as this piece by Harvard’s School of Public Health reminds us, the stimulus of frequent social contact certainly contributes to longevity.
Culture plays a huge role as well. According to Medium contributor @mia100.story,
“Korea often sees co-living with parents as an act of deep respect and responsibility. … In Korean society, it’s common to hear someone say, “I live with my parents to take care of them.” That phrase goes beyond physical cohabitation. It reflects a deeply rooted cultural value: that raising a child comes with the expectation of repayment, not in money, but in presence and support.
This mindset stems from the Confucian concept of filial piety (효, hyo) — a moral virtue of respect and care for one’s parents. Even in modern Korea, this value persists as a powerful cultural undercurrent.”
Similarly, this is an implicit part of the social fabric in many Caribbean and African societies, as many seniors continue to contribute highly relevant service to community, and occupy valued social roles, well beyond ‘retirement.’
And…Reason #3
“I agree with you,” my friend said after I had finished my spiel. “I think it’s completely valid for some personalities,” he added, before sharing that as an “inveterate loner,” he was perfectly happy on his own until he got married.
Sure, I responded. That made sense too.
It was he who brought up a final part of this equation. In many places, it’s easier for a single, adult daughter to live with her parents until marriage, than it would be for an adult son. That’s because traditionally, it has been socially important for sons to show they can take care of their future spouse and family by buying a home.
So, in that sense, maybe I have it a little easier.
But the broader takeaway here is about the lifelong benefits for all involved — including networking/career benefits — such as deepening social connections with, and heck, enjoying the company of people significantly older or younger than ourselves.
""",
