    AuthorId = usersArray[2].Id,
    Title = "The Silent Blockchain Revolution in Corporate Banking Transactions",
    ImageUri = "https://plus.unsplash.com/premium_photo-1677723582727-6bd31c0f5ff5?w=600&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MXx8VGhlJTIwU2lsZW50JTIwQmxvY2tjaGFpbiUyMFJldm9sdXRpb24lMjBpbiUyMENvcnBvcmF0ZSUyMEJhbmtpbmclMjBUcmFuc2FjdGlvbnN8ZW58MHx8MHx8fDA%3D",
    Description = """
When institutions explore emerging technologies like distributed ledger technologies and blockchains, they often gravitate toward private, permissioned solutions such as Corda or Hyperledger. However, recent news about growing interest from major players in public, decentralized blockchains suggests that practical applications are already beginning to emerge.
But are these truly decentralized systems, particularly Web3? And what about the challenges that public blockchains introduce? What does the near future hold for corporate banking transactions?
In this article, I share my professional journey that shaped my perspective and highlight the technologies I believe are best positioned to bring corporate transactions fully on-chain.
My perspective: where do I come from?
My passion for optimizing business processes and increasing profitability began at 19. I was determined to be competitive and had set my sights on reaching top management immediately after graduating from university. Since then, I’ve spent years helping banks, construction firms, and e-commerce companies grow their margins, while also improving the operational efficiency of government institutions.
At the height of my career in a private IT company, I saw a persistent bottleneck in payment gateways. The delays had become so entrenched that no one questioned them, but I did. I knew things could be faster.
This led me to take on the role of Product Owner for the digital services at Elcard (https://ipc.kg/), the national payment system of Kyrgyzstan. Over the next several years, my team and I launched a wide array of digital solutions and established ELQR as the central QR hub for interbank payments across the country.
Yet even with all these advancements, the core issue remained: businesses were still not receiving funds in real time. The inefficiencies had become so normalized that even the suggestion of an instant alternative was often met with skepticism. Whether real-time settlement truly leads to higher profitability remains an open question, one I intend to explore in my next piece. I have now joined the National Bank of the Kyrgyz Republic, where I work on research and development of a central bank digital currency (CBDC), the underlying technology of which will be blockchain, and the payment will be a settlement.
Corporate transactions on the blockchain
During my participation in the DLT Talents programme from Frankfurt School of Finance and Management Blockchain Center, JPMorgan introduced a compelling concept: using a stablecoin-like token, JPMD, to offer institutional clients faster, more seamless fund transfers on-chain. This announcement marked a key shift in the conversation.
So, corporations that want to increase process efficiency and explore blockchain technologies often turn to private blockchains. To meet regulatory requirements, the most heavily regulated players tend to build proprietary systems, where onboarding and customization can take up to a year, even for mid-level developers. However, the JPMorgan case introduces another option: Layer 2 solutions, which are built on top of public blockchains. Was it about enabling real business use cases in a compliant, interoperable manner? Let’s try to explore the technologies behind.
Possible technologies behind the corporate banking transactions on-chain
Layer 2
Blockchain can offer a more cost-effective and efficient alternative to traditional IT systems for a variety of purposes, including secure information exchange, controlled data access, and transparent transaction recording. To address the core scalability, improve transaction speed, and reduce the transaction cost, there is an increasing interest in Layer 2 solutions that can be deployed on top of the public blockchains. Layer 2 solution allows off-chain processing to increase transaction throughput and minimize the number of transactions recorded on the Layer 1 blockchain in order to reduce fees.
Types of Layer 2 solutions
State channels enable transactions between parties without requiring each transaction to be recorded on the mainnet. Only the final state of the channel is recorded on-chain, significantly improving the efficiency. Examples: Bitcoin Lightning network, Ethereum’s Rauden Network.
Sidechains are separate blockchains that run parallel to the main chain (Layer 1), and they don’t directly inherit Layer 1 security. On the contrary, they offer their solutions for security and consensus mechanisms. Examples: Polygon (Ethereum), Liquid Network (Bitcoin).
Rollups aggregate multiple transactions into a single transaction, which is then submitted to the main chain. Rollups inherit the security of Layer 1 while processing transactions off-chain. Examples: Arbitrum (Optimistic), zkSync (ZK-Rollups), Optimism (Optimistic).
ERC-2771 and ERC-5564
ERC-2771, in other words, the Meta-transaction solution was designed to address making calls from externally owned accounts (EOAs) without paying transaction fees, the gas fees covered by third parties (forwarders). The purpose of using the meta transaction could be to address the privacy issues, especially for corporate deals. With this Ethereum standard, the user signs a message off-chain, and the relayer contract submits it on-chain, covering the gas fee. This design was primarily introduced to improve the usability (gasless transaction) and onboarding. However, the interesting side effect of ERC-2771’s shield is that it protects the user’s on-chain identity because all meta transactions appear to originate from the forwarder’s address, not the end user’s address on the block explorers. Additionally, for the recipient, the ERC-5564 stealth address could be used.
Are these truly decentralized systems?
The promise of WEB3 was simple but ambitious: decentralize ownership, control, and value transfer, replacing intermediaries with code. In reality, the systems we call “decentralized” often rely on a complex mix of centralized components: trusted validators and infrastructure providers. Even popular public blockchains can have points of centralization: governance power concentrated in a small group of token holders, reliance on a few node operators, or dependency on centralized oracles and hosting services. All the above technologies for corporate deals are more likely the WEB2.5 technologies rather than WEB3.
Near future for corporate banking transactions on-chain
In the next few years, expect more hybrid blockchain architectures: public networks for settlement and verification, combined with permissioned layers or zero-knowledge modules for privacy and compliance. Central bank digital currencies (CBDCs) and regulated stablecoins will increasingly serve as settlement assets, enabling atomic delivery-versus-payment (DvP) transactions entirely on-chain.
Major financial institutions are already piloting these approaches, JPMorgan’s JPMD deposit token on a public Layer 2 is a prime example. If these models prove reliable, corporate adoption will accelerate, with on-chain deals moving from pilots to production in trade finance, loans, cross-border payments, and supply chain contracts.
The real question is not whether corporate deals will happen on-chain, they will, but how decentralized the infrastructure will truly be, and how effectively we balance openness with the operational and regulatory realities of global business.
""",
