{
    AuthorId = usersArray[1].Id,
    Title = "Mahmood Mamdani: What happens when categories replace systems",
    ImageUri = "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1581541043074-8051ec4508dc?w=600&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8OXx8Y2F0ZWdvcmllcyUyMHJlcGxhY2UlMjBzeXN0ZW1zfGVufDB8fDB8fHww",
    Description = """
Mahmood Mamdani isn’t a household name, but his work explains something most people feel without knowing how to articulate it: Societies don’t fall apart because people disagree. They fall apart when disagreement becomes fused with identity, when categories replace systems.
Where Madison studied factions and Ostrom studied shared resources, Mamdani studied the aftermath. He saw that societies fracture when political life hardens around identity categories instead of rules, negotiations, and shared institutions. Once identities become rigid, the categories do the thinking for you.
His work in East Africa, South Asia, and the Middle East circled the same dynamic: When politics operate through identity rather than structure, balance disappears. Colonial administrations created durable divisions by labeling people as “natives” or “settlers,” assigning rights and responsibilities based on category instead of citizenship. Everything that followed—representation, punishment, land allocation, even definitions of violence—flowed from the category, not the behavior.
The pattern was consistent:
People stopped seeing one another as individuals and began treating each other as types. Arguments became personal because they tied directly to who someone was, not the merits of the argument itself. Each group insisted that its identity determined the rules.
Once a system is organized around identity, laws begin to formalize conflict instead of stabilizing it. Public life shifts from negotiation to competition over whoever controls the categories closest to power.
This is Mamdani’s core warning: When a group can define categories, it no longer needs to define the argument. The system itself carries the argument for them.
Examples illustrate the mechanics:
In Rwanda, colonial powers turned fluid identities into fixed racial categories, replacing negotiation with inherited status and leaving the society permanently destabilized. In Sudan, tribal classifications reshaped land rights and obligations, ensuring that every political conflict would be interpreted through ethnicity. In Uganda, colonial patterns created a split between citizenship and identity, guaranteeing that most disagreements would escalate rather than resolve.
Different regions, same mechanism: certainty hardened into identity becomes a destabilizer.
This connects directly to the broader argument:
Madison warned against dominance by a single group. Ostrom showed how shared rules and distributed responsibility prevent imbalance. Mamdani shows what happens when none of that holds—when people collapse a complex political system into rigid categories and defend those categories as if survival depends on them.
This explains our modern reflex: when expanding someone’s frame feels like an attack. Nuance looks like betrayal, and balance? That starts to resemble disloyalty.
People aren’t inherently unreasonable. Their political identity is simply doing too much work. Once identity carries the whole argument, the entire system begins to slide.
""",
    Topics = appDbContext.Topics.Where(t => t.Id == 19 || t.Id == 31).ToList()
},
