{
    AuthorId = usersArray[1].Id,
    Title = "The Downward Trajectory of Adult Spirituality",
    ImageUri = "https://plus.unsplash.com/premium_photo-1664286587470-5c22bcc2897e?w=600&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MXx8VGhlJTIwRG93bndhcmQlMjBUcmFqZWN0b3J5JTIwb2YlMjBBZHVsdCUyMFNwaXJpdHVhbGl0eXxlbnwwfHwwfHx8MA%3D%3D",
    Description = """
It felt like the beginning of a new stage of life. I was scrolling on Facebook and saw that an old schoolmate posted his mother’s obituary. Are we at that stage of life already? I thought.
Soon, social media was feeding me more obituaries of mothers and fathers who followed her to the grave, people who I once called “Mr.” and “Mrs.” from the back of mini-vans.
The roles reversed long ago. One day, we called our parents for help. The next, we were the adults who cared for our aging parents. We laughed at their quirky habits that drove us crazy. We talked about cable bills and Roth IRAs at parties. We thought about who would take care of them if something happened to us.
Now, they were leaving.
Next came the divorces. Friends who married in high school and had children decided to part ways, not because they didn’t try but because they had tried everything and couldn’t figure it out.
There were addictions. Children with mental health issues. Fertility problems. It would start with a grown-up problem and the scripture passages on Instagram inevitably followed. My social media feed once littered with party pictures. Now, it’s Mary Oliver poems and twelve-step quotes.
This isn’t just my religious friends. It’s the partiers. The chronically single people who moved to the city for important jobs. The intellectuals.
As I approach my forties, it’s happening more. My middle aged peers are rediscovering spirituality.
When we were young, spirituality and morality were fused into one overwhelming domain of life. Good behavior earned one a connection with a higher power. The goodies carried their crosses. The baddies mostly seemed to care about crosses when it came time to get a tattoo.
When I worked as a counselor for people on work release, some skeptical prisoners had a word for religion that is discovered while in crisis. They called it “jailhouse religion” and wrote it off as something cheap and easy. “Why didn’t you read the Bible before?” they said.
It takes what it takes, I’d say, shrugging. I believe that God will use any means necessary to find us.
In my adult world, the split between “good” and “bad” has all but disappeared. The bad kids are posting scripture passages and the good kids are deconstructing their beliefs. Everyone is searching for something, not because we’ve earned anything, but because some life made us feel powerless and sent us looking for something other than our own way of proceeding.
I wouldn’t call it a mid-life awakening. I’d call it a deepening.
A lifelong Catholic who went to church every week told me that he discovered real spirituality after getting a DUI and attending AA. “That was just checking a box,” he told me, of his church-only days. “But character flaws, accountability, acceptance…this is the real spiritual stuff.”
A dear friend told me how battling her husband’s mental health issues as a team brought them closer together. They learned to talk about vulnerable things, support each other when things get hard and that their relationship could withstand long periods of strife. “It was like holding the iron to the fire,” she told me. “It was hard, but it brought us much closer.”
John of the Cross called it “the dark night of the soul.” Twelve step programmers call it “rock bottom.” Addicts and mystics seem to acknowledge it more than many speaking from pulpits, but spiritual gold is indeed hiding in the dark parts of life.
One mentor told me that by the time we reach our thirties, our sins are our sins. Most of us will take some of them to the grave. And increasingly, I see those deeply embedded wounds not as a barrier to God but as an access point. When we hit our limits, grace tends to follow.
As a therapist, I see it most starkly in people grieving. When someone loses a spouse or a father, they start connecting to the world in a new way. They don’t want to avoid pain, because it’s the pain that connects them to someone that they love. Instead, they learn to walk around with it. And once they stop resisting the pain, it becomes something else.
For some, pain offers a kind of surrender. One woman in a grief group told me that she was stuck. Once she stopped resisting her stuckness, she realized she was stuck for a reason and learned to embrace stillness.
For others, pain becomes a bittersweet balm and a magnet for a different kind of love, the kind of love that a child gets from his parents after an injury or a loss. A nun once described God as her father patting her back after the death of a beloved pet. There, there.
For others, pain simply connects them to a deceased loved one. And letting go of the pain would mean letting go of their love.
For those who have learned to grieve, the goal of life is no longer to feel good. It is to love — no matter what that feels like.
I don’t know when we reduced a religion based on the life of a brutally murdered Jewish man — one who was despised during his lifetime and died naked on a cross — into something aspirational. Or when religious platitudes like “everything happens for a reason” replaced a faith that has always included space for suffering.
It is fundamental to the Christian story that the way up is down. That suffering and death can be redemptive. That if one clings too long to the illusion of self-sufficiency and upward mobility, they may miss the upside logic of the Christian world, where the last are going to be first and death leads to new life.
Pain is part of the spiritual life. One never seeks it, but it always finds its way to those who are doing the risky work of living and loving. It has something to offer, if only we let it in.
""",
